The power of the üß†. Did you see it move? ü§Ø  Occupational therapists often use mirror therapy in outpatient rehabilitation settings to help stroke survivors improve their motor function and overall recovery. The therapy typically involves the use of a mirror that is placed in front of the affected limb, creating the illusion of movement. The therapist will then guide the patient through a series of movements, encouraging them to engage the affected limb and try to move it in sync with their non-affected limb. This can help retrain the brain and improve the patient's ability to control their affected limb. In addition to improving movement, mirror therapy can also help reduce pain and improve overall function, making it an essential part of stroke rehabilitation.  #strokerecovery #strokerehabilitation #strokeawareness #strokerehab #cva #cerebralvascularaccident #cva #occupationaltherapy #physicaltherapy #physicaltherapytiktok #physicaltherapyclinic #mirrortherapy

video_description: How Can a 20-week Old Baby Survive? #preemie  Significant medical advances have been made to increase the chances of survival for babies born as early as 20 weeks gestation. Previously considered extremely premature, these infants now have a fighting chance at life due to advances in neonatal intensive care and medical technology. In recent years, improvements in respiratory support, such as surfactant therapy and advanced ventilator techniques, have played a vital role in helping the immature lungs of these babies function. Neonatal specialists have developed strategies to manage complications associated with prematurity, including respiratory distress syndrome, intraventricular hemorrhage, and infections. Advancements in nutrition and feeding techniques have also contributed to the improved outcomes for these infants. The development of specialized formulas and techniques for delivering nutrients intravenously or through feeding tubes has enhanced their growth and development. Additionally, the advent of sophisticated monitoring systems has allowed healthcare providers to closely monitor the vital signs and overall well-being of these fragile infants.
